    <subsection xml:id="subsec-cylsurf">
      <title>Cylinder Surfaces</title>
      <p>
        Our previous examples in this section show how to create a variety of interesting curves on the <m>xy</m>-plane. What happens if we consider these same equations in three dimensions? Let's look at an example like <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m>. If we consider the graph of  <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m> in 2D, then we get a parabola centered at <m>(1,-2)</m>. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="para-ex2">
        <caption>A plot of <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane with five points highlighted</caption>
        <image width="75%" xml:id="img-para-ex2">
          <description>   </description>
          <sageplot>
            var('t')
            tvals=[-2,-1,0,1/2,5/3]
            plot9=parametric_plot(((t^2+1)/2,t-2),(t,-3,3),color="black",axes=True,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],gridlines=True)
            for s in tvals:
                plot9+=point(((s^2+1)/2,s-2),color="blue",size=20)
            show(plot9,aspect_ratio=1,xmin=-2,xmax=4,ymin=-5,ymax=1)
          </sageplot>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        If we want to look at the graph of <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m> in 3D, we are considering all of the <m>(x,y,z)</m> points that will satisfy this equation. So if we pick <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> values that satisfy <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m>, then ANY choice of <m>z</m> will satisfy the given question. So for the each of the highlighted points on <xref ref="para-ex2" />, we can extend the graph of <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m> parallel to the <m>z</m>-axis. <xref ref="cylsurfex1" /> shows how the points on the parabola (in black) can be extended to include any <m>z</m> coordinate.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="cylsurfex1">
        <caption>A plot of <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m> generating curve and several rulings</caption>
          <interactive xml:id="interactive-cylsurfex1" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
            <slate surface="sage">
              from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
              var('t')
              scale=6
              plot10=axes(scale,1,color="black",frame=False)+text3d("x",(scale+0.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+0.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+0.5),fontsize=30)
              tvals=[-2,-1,0,1/2,5/3]
              plot10+=parametric_plot3d(((t^2+1)/2,t-2,0),(t,-3,3),color="black",axes=True,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],gridlines=True)
              for s in tvals:
                  plot10+=point3d(((s^2+1)/2,s-2,0),color="blue",size=20)
                  plot10+=line([((s^2+1)/2,s-2,scale),((s^2+1)/2,s-2,-scale)],color="green")
              show(plot10,aspect_ratio=1)
            </slate>
          </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Extending all points from the circle <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane parallel to the <m>z</m>-axis will give a surface. This kind of surface is called a <term>cylinder surface</term>, the two dimensional curve you use to make the surface is called the <term>generating curve</term>, and the lines that extend in the direction of the missing variable are called <term>rulings</term>. In <xref ref="cylsurfex2" />, the surface is plotted in blue, the generating curve in black, and the rulings in green. This surface is called a parabolic cylinder surface because the generating curve is a parabola.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="cylsurfex2">
        <caption>A plot of the cylinder surface <m>(y+2)=\frac{t^2-1}{2}</m> with generating curve and several rulings</caption>
